narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned how to apply concepts we learned in class to new examples, rather than just do the same problems with different numbers. We covered limits, derivatives, function transformations, and different types of functions in depth.

I was able to learn how to do, basic calculus problems, such as optimization and finding derivatives. Additionally, the start of the course went over more basic algebra principles as well as graphing.
I learned lots about how to manage my studies, whether problem sets, concept checks, etc. and how to use accumulate the information for exams.
Algebraic skills, how to plan out steps, basic introduction to calculus
This course really gave me a solid foundation in calculus as well as in some other algebra skills that I hadnt really learned before.
I developed many skills that help me in calculus.

In this course I learned push through adversity and finish, although certain marks on assessments might not have reflected. I got a deep understanding of what it means to keep going and anchor in when it gets rough. I also learned that certain study habits are better for me than others
I developed an adequate foundation for harder calculus concepts and strengthened my previous knowledge in pre calculus concepts.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: well-organized lessons, well-organized Canvas page, lots of ULAs and office hours available, concept checks 

Weaknesses: weekly workshops were slightly long, textbook was sometimes confusing

The instruction was very good, and the office hours were quite helpful. I think the course could be improved by allowing students to ask for help on the concept checks and sometimes the math workshops for a little long.
The problem sets are very hard and time-consuming. Rather, less question length and more emphasis on practicing the core concepts of Calculus 1 would improve this course.

strengths: consistent help from ULAs for psets
weakness: too rushed on some topics, not enough review time in class
I think a strength was the office hours were very helpful and engaging. A weakness might have been that the workshops were not the most helpful.
I liked the tecshing style. However, it could be improved by slowing the course time down, sometimes we go too fast.
I think this course was taught well, it was very engaging.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend this course to someone who has never taken a Calculus class or has only taken an Intro course. This course does slowly teach new concepts yet the workload includes problem sets, concept checks, and weekly workshops. There is a lot of professor and ULA support.
Yes, it was a good structured way to be introduced to calculus.
Yes. Su Ji rocks!
yes, if you need some algebraic understanding of calculus for a specific purpose
Yes! It is a great intro level course for math if you dont have a strong foundation with lots of instructor and ULA support.
Yes I would.

Yes definitely, if only because of the professor. Professor Hong was great at teaching the concepts and making us get engaged. The workload was also not terrible and it all related to what was covered in class.
